# Inject Config Sections by Pointer, Not Scattered Fields

When a component (a service handler, engine, task-processor reader/factory,
matcher, …) needs tunables from a `config` section, pass a pointer to that
whole section — e.g. `*config.RunServiceConfig`, `*config.TaskProcessorConfig`,
`*config.MatchingEngineConfig` — into its constructor and read fields off it.
Do NOT thread the individual fields (`matchingAPITimeout`,
`waitForHistoryMaxTimeout`, …) as separate constructor parameters.

## Why

Adding a new knob to the section should not churn every constructor signature
and every call site between the bootstrap and the component. With the whole
section injected, a new field is read at the use site only.

## Rules

- **Constructor takes `*config.XyzConfig`**, stored as an unexported `cfg`
  field; the component reads `h.cfg.SomeKnob` at the use site.
- **Pass the whole section, not the top-level `config.Config`.** A component
  depends only on its own section (`&cfg.RunEngine`, `&cfg.TaskProcessor`),
  never the entire `config.Config` — that would hide which section it uses and
  couple it to unrelated config.
- **Pointer, not value.** Config is read-only after startup; a pointer avoids
  copying and makes "same config" identity obvious. Panic in the constructor if
  the pointer is nil (required dependency — see no-unnecessary-nil-checks).
- **Still applies with constructor injection** (see no-setter-injection): the
  config pointer is a normal constructor argument, never a `SetConfig` setter.
- This is the standard for `RunsService` + `RunEngine` (`*config.RunServiceConfig`)
  and should be followed by the other components (task processor, matching, …)
  as they are touched.

## Examples

<bad>

```go
// Bad: individual fields threaded through the constructor.
func NewRunsServiceHandler(
    ..., matchingAPITimeout time.Duration,
    waitForHistoryMaxTimeout time.Duration,
    waitForHistorySafetyBuffer time.Duration, logger log.Logger,
) *RunsServiceHandler { ... }

// Adding one knob forces a new param here AND at every call site.
```

</bad>

<good>

```go
// Good: the whole section pointer; new knobs are read at the use site only.
func NewRunsServiceHandler(
    ..., historyNotifier historynotify.NotifierManager,
    cfg *config.RunServiceConfig, logger log.Logger,
) *RunsServiceHandler {
    if cfg == nil { panic("NewRunsServiceHandler: cfg must not be nil") }
    return &RunsServiceHandler{..., cfg: cfg, ...}
}

// Bootstrap: pass the section, not the whole Config, not scattered fields.
h := NewRunsServiceHandler(..., historyNotifier, &cfg.RunEngine, logger)

// Use site:
timeout := h.cfg.MatchingServiceAPITimeout
```

</good>

## Review checklist

Reject:

- A constructor with multiple scalar params that are all fields of one config
  section — collapse them into a `*config.XyzConfig`.
- A component taking the whole `config.Config` when it only reads one section.
- Passing a config section by value where it will be stored long-term.
